1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,000
Today I'll show you how ChatGPT can be turned into real learning tools, not just a translator.

2
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:15,000
And today I'll speak not in general terms, but will use specific prompts and queries that you'll also be able to reproduce.

3
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:21,000
As an example, today I'll be showing everything at the A1 level, but this video is not only for beginners.

4
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:26,000
You'll be able to adapt all of this too, because we're going to build a real learning system.

5
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:33,000
And the ready-made prompts for your level you can find in the pinned comment under the link in my Telegram channel.

6
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:35,000
And our first step is the foundation.

7
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:39,000
You need to know exactly what your current English level is.

8
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:43,000
It's not okay to write that you're somewhere between A2 or B1.

9
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:49,000
You need to know your exact level, because otherwise ChatGPT won't be able to build a program specifically for you.

10
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:53,000
It'll be either too easy or too hard the other way around.

11
00:00:54,000 --> 00:01:01,000
For this case I have a ready-made prompt for you that you can copy and paste into your chat.

12
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:02,000
Let me read it now.

13
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:05,000
You are an experienced English teacher.

14
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:07,000
Help me determine my English level.

15
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:10,000
Create a series of tasks that test.

16
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:13,000
Vocabulary, grammar, reading comprehension, speaking.

17
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:16,000
Go step by step, gradually increasing the difficulty.

18
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:19,000
After my answers explain what it means for my level.

19
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:21,000
And tell me what it is.

20
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:27,000
And in 20-30 minutes you'll have a real understanding of where you are now and where you need to go next.

21
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:36,000
And here's another critically important point — a mistake I see all the time: people open too many chats and try to learn in all of them.

22
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:42,000
But it's very important to open only one chat and learn specifically in that one.

23
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:46,000
Because then that chat remembers everything about you.

24
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:54,000
What mistakes you made, what you said incorrectly, what you've already covered, what needs to be reinforced again.

25
00:01:54,000 --> 00:02:01,000
And when you open new chats, that memory doesn't carry over and you basically start from scratch every time.

26
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:06,000
So we stick to one chat, one teacher.

27
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:08,000
Alright, now our second step.

28
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:13,000
Now we're going to create the teacher who will be teaching us.

29
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:17,000
Let's read through this prompt, but you'll be able to copy it later.

30
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:20,000
I am learning English, my level is A1.

31
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:22,000
Here you can insert your own level.

32
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:24,000
Teach me like a patient teacher.

33
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:30,000
From simple to complex, in small steps, with constant repetition, without overload.

34
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:32,000
Work with me in one chat.

35
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:34,000
Remember my typical mistakes.

36
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:36,000
Come back to them later.

37
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:43,000
First explain, then give practice, then repeat, speak simply and clearly.

38
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:46,000
And with this step you're doing something really important.

39
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:54,000
You're not just opening another random chat, you're creating your own permanent, stable teacher.

40
00:02:54,000 --> 00:03:02,000
So now you've created your teacher, you've given them a goal — let's move on to practice.

41
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:08,000
The next step is to get some ready-made phrases from them that match our level.

42
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:10,000
What do we write to them?

43
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:17,000
Give me 10 very simple English phrases for the A1 level on the topic of introductions without grammar explanations.

44
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:25,000
Look, here you can change both the level and the topic you want to get the phrases on, but overall I think the logic is clear.

45
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:31,000
And look at what it will send us — I'll add a screenshot here.

46
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:35,000
Here it goes, sending right away.

47
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:39,000
Great, here are 10 very simple phrases for the A1 level on the topic of introductions.

48
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:46,000
Basically it did its job — it sent you not just words but complete ready-made phrases.

49
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:54,000
And I think you should already know that you really need to learn a language not with individual words but with ready-made language chunks.

50
00:03:54,000 --> 00:03:58,000
Our next stage will be listening and a prompt for listening.

51
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:02,000
Read these phrases out loud slowly.

52
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:04,000
And now I'll show you how this works.

53
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:10,000
Of course. I'll now read them clearly and slowly so it's easy for you to repeat.

54
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:12,000
Ready? Let's go.

55
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:14,000
First. Hello.

56
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:16,000
Second. Hi.

57
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:18,000
Third. My name is Anna.

58
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:20,000
Fourth. I am Anna.

59
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:22,000
Fifth. What is your name?

60
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:24,000
Sixth. Nice to meet you.

61
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:26,000
Seventh. I am from Ukraine.

62
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:28,000
Eighth. Where are you from?

63
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Ninth. How are you?

64
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:32,000
Tenth. I am fine.

65
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:34,000
I'll repeat as many times as needed.

66
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:36,000
If needed, tell it again.

67
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:38,000
Just like that.

68
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:41,000
Look at what's important here. You can listen to this just once.

69
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:44,000
I really recommend listening to it more than once.

70
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:47,000
Why? So that you'll be fixing it in your head.

71
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:50,000
Your brain will process it better.

72
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:54,000
And will later be able to recognize it in real language, in real life.

73
00:04:54,000 --> 00:05:00,000
And will also later be able to suggest these phrases when you're speaking English yourself.

74
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:02,000
So listen as much as possible.

75
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:09,000
By the way, regarding how to listen to all this, I'll add a screenshot here right now.

76
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:13,000
So you need to press it to have what was written read aloud.

77
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:16,000
Our next step will be reading.

78
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:22,000
And not just any reading, but reading specifically what you've just been working with.

79
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:33,000
So we'll be polishing those phrases and expressions that you already read and heard just now, and what prompt we'll use for that.

80
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:34,000
Look.

81
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:37,000
Create a monologue story, a reading text.

82
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:40,000
Six sentences for the A1 level with these phrases.

83
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:50,000
It should sound like natural language, one paragraph, sentences logically connected, no lists and no separate phrases, so it can be said in one breath.

84
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:54,000
And now I'll show you what it created for me.

85
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:57,000
Here I'm adding a screenshot of its response.

86
00:05:57,000 --> 00:05:59,000
And what to do with this.

87
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:02,000
You can read it out loud to yourself.

88
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:04,000
More than once if needed.

89
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:10,000
You can ask it to read it out loud again through that button I already showed you.

90
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:17,000
And another important thing here — your brain recognizes something it heard somewhere before and starts to recall it.

91
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:20,000
And in that moment you're really learning.

92
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:24,000
And now we're going to move on to grammar.

93
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:28,000
But I'm not going to ask it to write me the rules of usage now.

94
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:31,000
I'll ask it to simply explain this to me.

95
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:34,000
And look at what we can write to it.

96
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:45,000
Look at what it replies to me.

97
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:48,000
I am, я є — this is what you say about yourself.

98
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:54,000
When you want to say who you are, what you're like, how you feel, you start with I am.

99
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:56,000
And life examples follow.

100
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:58,000
In my opinion, the explanation is great.

101
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:06,000
There are no complex terms, just logically clear, and for beginners it's simply wonderful.

102
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:11,000
Of course, if it's a different level, it'll be a bit more complex.

103
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:13,000
In the prompts you'll see all of this.

104
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:15,000
But for now the logic is like this.

105
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:17,000
Well, and now comes my favorite stage.

106
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:21,000
The stage where we start talking with our chat.

107
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:26,000
Again, through this button here we need to switch to conversation mode with it.

108
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:28,000
And what do we say?

109
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:36,000
Let's now do a simple dialogue in English for the A1 level.

110
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:40,000
You are a new person to me and ask me simple questions one by one.

111
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:44,000
Of course, no problem.

112
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:48,000
Let's start a simple dialogue and I'll ask questions one by one.

113
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:50,000
First question.

114
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:52,000
What is your name?

115
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:04,000
I'm from Ukraine.

116
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:14,000
I love cooking and working out.

117
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:28,000
I think you understand that I'm currently learning English.

118
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:32,000
Of course.

119
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:34,000
I just wanted to see that you understand.

120
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:36,000
You're doing well.

121
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:05,000
When you answer, make use of it.

122
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:23,000
Help me write three simple sentences about myself in English for the A1 level.

123
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:27,000
Now I'll show you what it replied to me.

124
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:29,000
Adding it.

125
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:33,000
It has templates that I can use.

126
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:37,000
And then it says it's your turn, meaning you should write those three sentences to it.

127
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:45,000
In this case, when you write your sentences to it, it will correct you if something is wrong.

128
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:49,000
Or on the contrary praise you if you wrote everything correctly.

129
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:51,000
And now a very important point.

130
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:55,000
After each session you need to track your progress.

131
00:09:55,000 --> 00:10:00,000
You need to give this machine a prompt as well.

132
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:08,000
Make a short summary of the lesson — what we covered, what mistakes keep repeating, to review next time.

133
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:10,000
No more than 100 words.

134
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:24,000
Look, you can paste all of this both at the end of this lesson and at the beginning of the next one, so you don't forget what you've already done and can pay attention to what you need to work on more.

135
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:32,000
And now there'll be a very logical question: you've practiced, what do I do next, how do I do all this on my own?

136
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:38,000
And I'll tell you — you don't need to reinvent the wheel because I've already done it for you.

137
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:44,000
You just need to copy this prompt and follow the roadmap we've already created.

138
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:46,000
Look at what the prompt is.

139
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:50,000
Conduct a daily English lesson for the A1 level.

140
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:52,000
One lesson, one day.

141
00:10:52,000 --> 00:10:54,000
Work step by step.

142
00:10:54,000 --> 00:10:56,000
Two to three minutes.

143
00:10:56,000 --> 00:11:00,000
In repetition use the same words and structures as before.

144
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:04,000
After each step pause and wait for my next.

145
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:06,000
Lesson structure. Short review.

146
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:08,000
Short explanation of a new topic.

147
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:10,000
Eight to ten simple phrases.

148
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:12,000
Read them out loud.

149
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:14,000
Short connected text.

150
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:16,000
Simple explanation of the meaning of structures.

151
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:18,000
Short dialogue.

152
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:20,000
Three sentences of writing.

153
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:22,000
Speak simply and don't overload.

154
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:24,000
And that's it.

155
00:11:24,000 --> 00:11:28,000
ChatGPT will guide you further like a real teacher.

156
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:30,000
It's just magic, I think.

157
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:32,000
And regarding these prompts.

158
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:36,000
They are written for a general learning system.

159
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:44,000
If you need a specific topic or want to look at a specific grammar structure and so on, you can of course adjust them.

160
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:46,000
So adapt them.

161
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:48,000
ChatGPT is not a tutor.

162
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:56,000
But with a well-built system you can turn it into a truly working practice tool.

163
00:11:56,000 --> 00:12:06,000
So the main thing here is to create this very system so that it's not chaotic but structured, the way we broke it down today.

164
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:08,000
Because that's exactly how our brain will absorb everything best.

165
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:14,000
So if you found this useful, interesting, and enjoyable — I'd really appreciate your support.

166
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:18,000
Like, comment, subscribe.

167
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:32,000
And I want to remind you that below this video and in the pinned comment you'll find a link to my Telegram channel where all the prompts for every level will be collected.

168
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:34,000
Bye!

